Introduction</h1><p class="P30">The Dynamic Cluster Scaling Engine (DCSE) is a software project to scale High Performance Compute (HPC) Clusters, increasing or decreasing the size of a cluster by managing the availability of “worker” nodes (the physical or virtual servers to which cluster jobs are farmed out for processing) according to real-time demand.</p><p class="P10"><span
class="T11">The DCSE allows HPC stakeholders to reduce </span><span class="T12">both</span><span class="T11"> the initial capital investment required to build a HPC cluster </span><span class="T12">and the considerable running costs in terms of energy required to run such systems. </span></p><p class="P31">Initial investment costs can be reduced by the DCSE via “cloudbursting” (expanding the cluster by adding virtualised worker node instances in public “cloud” resources) at times of peak demand, reducing the number of physical worker nodes required at the procurement stage.</p><p class="P11"><span class="T12">Running costs can be lowered by the DCSE by powering on and off cluster worker nodes </span><span class="T17">dynamically</span><span class="T12"> according to demand.</span></p><h2 class="P56"><a id="a__1_1_Background"><span/></a><a name="__RefHeading__527_212782876"/>1.1 Background</h2><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__1_1_1_High_Performance_Compute_Cluster_Overview"><span/></a><a name="__RefHeading__
529_212782876"/><span class="T3">1.1.</span><span class="T4">1</span><span class="T3"> High Performance Compute Cluster Overview</span></h3><p class="P32">High Performance Compute (HPC) Clusters are systems which combine the power of a number of hardware resources to perform computationally-expensive tasks, which would be difficult or overly time-consuming to run on a single machine. Examples include climate modelling/prediction, engineering simulations, processing genomic data, financial data modelling, and automotive design.</p><p class="P32">While architectures and implementations differ significantly between various HPC system, clusters typically have most, if not all, of the following features:</p><ul><li><p class="P33" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">•</span>A small numer of (often just one) “head” or “master” nodes, to which user jobs are directly submitted<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P33" style="margin-left:0cm;
"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">•</span>A large number of “Compute” or “worker” nodes, the servers which process the jobs.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><div class="P34" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">•</span><span class="T13">Shared storage, </span><span class="T14">attached to and distributed by one or more “storage” nodes, often using a </span><span class="T14">parallel file system such as Lustre</span><span class="T14"><span class="Footnote_20_anchor" title="Footnote: http://www.lustre.org"><a href="#ftn1" id="body_ftn1">1</a></span></span><span class="T14"> or GPFS</span><span class="T14"><span class="Footnote_20_anchor" title="Footnote: GPFS is a trademark of IBM corp. http://www-03.ibm.com/systems/software/gpfs/"><a href="#ftn2" id="body_ftn2">2</a></span></span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </div></li><li><p class="P35" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols"
style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">•</span>A high speed ethernet or infiniband (or hybrid) network connecting the resources.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ul><p class="P15"> </p><p class="P36">A typical simple HPC cluster implementation showing the core components above can be seen in the following diagram:</p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="P12"><!--Next 'div' is emulating the top hight of a draw:frame.--><div style="height:0.469cm;"> </div><!--Next '

allocate the jobs to the available resources on “compute” nodes. If sufficient resources are unavailable, the jobs are queued until such time as they can be run.</p><div class="P16"><span class="T15">Jobs which require more resources than are available on a single “compute” node can be run on many nodes in parallel. Typically, these jobs need to communicate with one another using some form of message passing, such as OpenMP</span><span class="T15"><span class="Footnote_20_anchor" title="Footnote: http://openmp.org/wp/"><a href="#ftn3" id="body_ftn3">3</a></span></span><span class="T15"> or OpenMPI</span><span class="T15"><span class="Footnote_20_anchor" title="Footnote: http://www.open-mpi.org/"><a href="#ftn4" id="body_ftn4">4</a></span></span><span class="T15">.</span></div><p class="P17"><span class="T16">Upon completion of the job, outputs or results are generally returned to the user</span><span class="T18">s home directory or other location specified in the users job submission script.</span></p><h3

>st</span><span class="T21"> 2013</span><span class="T21"><span class="Footnote_20_anchor" title="Footnote: Los Alamos National Laboratoy Press Release – March 29th 2013. http://www.lanl.gov/newsroom/news-releases/2013/March/03.29-end-of-roadrunner.php"><a href="#ftn8" id="body_ftn8">8</a></span></span><span class="T21">. </span><span class="T22">The initial procurement cost for the system had been an estimated $100 million.</span><span class="T22"><span class="Footnote_20_anchor" title="Footnote: Source: http://searchdatacenter.techtarget.com/definition/IBM-Roadrunner"><a href="#ftn9" id="body_ftn9">9</a></span></span></div><h4 class="P69"><a id="a__1_1_2_2_Running_Costs"><span/></a><a name="__RefHeading__535_212782876"/>1.1.2.2 Running Costs</h4><p class="P39">In addition to hardware costs, HPC systems consume massive amounts of power, which combined with cooling costs and staffing needs result in ongoing operational outlay that can prove prohibitively expensive.</p><p class="P39">The following table

ongoing running costs by adapting the size of the cluster in accordance with demand.</span><span class="T30">It will seek to accomplish this by dynamically provisioning (and retiring) compute resources, both physical and cloud based, according to demand and usage trends.</span></p><p class="P44">Specifically, the project sets out to achieve two primary objectives:</p><ol><li><p class="P45" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Numbering_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">1.</span>To reduce energy consumption (and therefore running costs) by adaptively scaling the cluster within it's physical resource pool.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P45" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Numbering_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">2.</span>To allow the cluster to expand beyond its physical resource pool by dynamically provisioning cloud based compute resources during peak demand.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ol><p class="P44">In achieving the
objectives specified above, it is hoped the proposed system will conform to a number of additional specifications in order to increase its usefulness:</p><ul><li><p class="P46" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">•</span><span class="T31">Modularity</span><span class="T30"> – Where possible and desirable, the solution should be deployed in sub-components which are capable of providing functionality independently, to facilitate re-use in other projects </span><span class="T38">or replacement with other products.</span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P47" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">•</span><span class="T30">Heterogeneity –</span><span class="T32"> In order to be usable across a range of differing cluster architectures and software stacks, the solution must be generic in nature, </span><span class="T33">capable of interacting with multiple Resource
Managers, Power Interfaces, and Public Cloud APIs.</span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ul><h2 class="P57"><a id="a__1_3_Brief_Overview_of_Proposed_System"><span/></a><a name="__RefHeading__657_212782876"/><span class="T34">1.3 </span><span class="T35">Brief </span><span class="T34">Overview of Proposed System</span></h2><p class="P48">In line with the objectives specified above, the proposed system consists of a number of elements as seen in the following table. class="T37">hile processing</span><span class="T36"> jobs.</span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P51" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">•</span>Widespread variance amongst Resource Managers, Cloud APIs, and Hardware Power Interfaces present a unique challenge in the creation of generic interfaces.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P51" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm">•</span>Cloud integration is a relatively new concept. Many HPC clusters do not alreay utilise public cloud offerings, and integrating public clouds with private clusters can involve a significant undertaking in laying the foundations for cloudbursting.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ul><p class="P52"> </p><h2 class="P59"><a id="a__1_5_Report_Roadmap"><span/></a><a name="__RefHeading__743_212782876"/>1.5 Report Roadmap</h2><p class="P53">Section 2 will further examine the
underlying architecture of the proposed system, outlining in detail the design and composition of each of the subcomponents in turn.</p><p class="P53">Section 3 will outline a procedure for the creation of additional vendor-specific drivers to cater for alternative (or new) Resource Managers, Cloud APIs, and Hardware Power Interfaces.</p><p class="P53">Section 4 will focus on the projects implementation and testing procedures, before section 5 provides a concluding analysis of the results of the implementation and its effectiveness measured against the original aims and objectives of the project.</p><p class="P53">Appendix A contains the source code for the project, while Appendix B contains the documentation for the system itself.
